{{Infobox language |name=Daats'iin |nativename= |states=[[Ethiopia]] |region=[[Benishangul-Gumuz Region]] |ethnicity=[[Gumuz people|Gumuz]] |speakers=300 |ref=e19 |date=2015 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Komuz languages|Komuz]] |fam3=[[Gumuz languages|Gumuz]] |glotto=none |iso3=dtn }}
'''Daats'iin''' is a [[Gumuz language]] of western [[Ethiopia]]. It was first reported in 2013 and described by Colleen Ahland in 2014. She has described it further in 2016.<ref>Colleen Ahland. 2016. Daatsʼíin, a newly identified undocumented language of western Ethiopia: A preliminary examination. In Doris L. Payne, Sara Pacchiarotti & Mokaya Bosire (eds.), ''Diversity in African languages'', 417–449. Berlin: Language Science Press.</ref> Of the other Gumuz languages, Daats'íin has the greatest lexical similarity to Southern Gumuz, but the two groups communicate in [[Arabic]] or [[Amharic]].<ref name=Ahland>[http://www-01.sil.org/iso639-3/cr_files/2015-054.pdf]</ref>
The community of speakers is in western Ethiopia, very near the [[Sudan]] border, just north of where the [[Blue Nile River]] crosses from Ethiopia into Sudan.<ref>map on p. 419. Colleen Ahland. 2016. Daatsʼíin, a newly identified undocumented language of western Ethiopia: A preliminary examination. In Doris L. Payne, Sara Pacchiarotti & Mokaya Bosire (eds.), ''Diversity in African languages'', 417–449. Berlin: Language Science Press.</ref>
==Grammar== Daats'íin has several grammatical differences from other Gumuz languages. Verbs inflect for [[Grammatical aspect|aspect]] ([[Perfective and imperfective|perfective&ndash;imperfective]]) rather than for tense (future&ndash;non-future). Verbs are [[Polysynthetic language|polysynthetic]] in all languages, but the order of the morphemes differs in Daats'iin, and some morphemes that occur in one language do not occur in the other(s).<ref name=Ahland/> "The major constituent order in Daats'íin clauses tend to be AVO/SV."<ref>p. 440. Colleen Ahland. 2016. Daatsʼíin, a newly identified undocumented language of western Ethiopia: A preliminary examination. In Doris L. Payne, Sara Pacchiarotti & Mokaya Bosire (eds.), ''Diversity in African languages'', 417–449. Berlin: Language Science Press.</ref>
